## 3. Detailed substrate behaviour

The j_BACL distribution across 200 records:

| j_BACL | Count | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| **−1** | 48 | V_2 = f_float − ulp(f_float) (sqrt rounded down then squared, landed one ulp below f) |
| **0**  | 100 | V_2 = f_float exactly (sqrt squared cleanly back to f) |
| **+1** | 52 | V_2 = f_float + ulp(f_float) (sqrt rounded up then squared, landed one ulp above f) |

The integer-j distribution is bounded `|j| ≤ 1`, a direct consequence of correctly-rounded sqrt: the rounding error |R − √f| ≤ ½·ulp(R), so |R² − f| ≤ ulp(f) (modulo binade boundary effects which never crossed here). This is **tighter than the c2 lattice theorem requires** — the theorem allows arbitrary integer j; the sqrt-specific bound restricts to `j ∈ {−1, 0, +1}`. Conjecture C is honoured: V_2 ≥ 2^k for f ∈ [2^k, 2^(k+1)) in all 200 records (the j = −1 cases stay above the binade floor by many ulps since f ≫ ulp).

**The substrate fingerprint of this fixture is: c_schw is on the integer-ulp lattice, with three-valued mantissa pattern {−1, 0, +1}.** Nothing else is there. The σ1 = 1.000 baseline reflects the linear scaling `ulp(f_float) ~ const · f_float ~ const · (r − 2)` near the horizon, *not* a geometric blow-up exponent.

